{"actual_usd":0.1256,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":213,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24481,"reply":"\"I think it was the same body, made new without ceasing to be his.\" *I rub a thumb over a dusting of flour on my apron and glance toward the sunlit bakery door, where the heat from the oven keeps pressing at my back.* \"Same wounds, same Lord, same flesh that had been nailed up there — but raised into glory, so he wasn't merely put back the way he was before.\"\n\n*I twirl a gray-streaked strand of hair once, thinking it through.* \"That's why the stories feel so strange in just that way. He can be touched, he can eat, the wounds are still there — and yet people miss him at first, like their eyes have to catch up to a truth too big for ordinary seeing. I don't take that to mean he was somebody else. More like resurrection is continuity and transformation both, and our little categories creak under the weight of it.\"\n\n\"If you like, we can tug on the Emmaus bit next, because I think that one says a lot.\"","rolling_24h_usd":66.53888999999998,"run_id":"844ca499-3d6c-4ee5-b955-c7014e2bda21"}
